.TH _PRINTF 3 "January 2026" "1.0" "Holberton C Library"
.SH NAME
_printf \- produce output according to a format
.SH SYNOPSIS
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The _printf() function produces output according to a format string and
a variable number of arguments.

The format string is composed of zero or more directives. A directive
is either:

.IP "\-"
a sequence of characters that are copied verbatim to the output, or
.IP "\-"
a conversion specification, which starts with the '%' character
and specifies how subsequent arguments are converted for output.

This implementation supports the following conversion specifiers:

.TP
.c
Print a single character.
.TP
.s
Print a string of characters.
.TP
%
Print a literal percent sign.
.TP
.d, .i
Print a signed decimal integer.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, _printf() returns the number of characters printed
(excluding the null byte used to end output).  

If an error occurs (for example, if the format string is NULL,
or a lone '%' is at the end of the format), the function returns -1.

.SH ERRORS
Errors may occur if a NULL pointer is passed as the format string
or other invalid arguments. No global variables are used.

.SH EXAMPLE
The following call:

.nf
_printf("Hello %c %s %% %d %i\n", 'A', "world", 42, -123);
.fi

Produces:

.nf
Hello A world % 42 -123
.fi

